        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><h3>ETF vs Index Fund: Which is better for the S&P 500?</h3></summary>
          <p>Both ETFs (Exchange-Traded Funds) and Mutual Index Funds are excellent ways to invest in the S&P 500. ETFs are traded like regular stocks throughout the day and often have lower minimum investments, making them slightly more flexible for beginners. Mutual index funds only trade once a day but are perfect for automated, set-and-forget investing.</p>
        </details>

        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary><h3>Can you lose all your money in the S&P 500?</h3></summary>
          <p>For you to lose all your money in an S&P 500 index fund, all 500 of the largest U.S. companies (like Apple, Microsoft, Amazon, etc.) would have to go bankrupt simultaneously. While your portfolio value will fluctuate and can drop significantly during bear markets, the chance of it going to absolute zero is virtually non-existent.</p>
